<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 12:7<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I29fbc4d0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>12.</label.designator><headtext>Burdens and Presumptions</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id72176aa682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>12:7.</label.designator><headtext>Nature of presumptions</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Former O.C.G.A. § 24-1-1 defined presumptions as inferences drawn by human experience from the connection of cause and effect and from observations of human conduct.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b91b6d074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] The new Georgia Evidence Code provides that <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[p]resumptions are either of law or of fact. <eos/><bos/>Presumptions of law are conclusions and inferences which the law draws from given facts. <eos/><bos/>Presumptions of fact shall be exclusively questions for the jury, to be decided by the ordinary test of human experience.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7b91b6d174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] For example, there is a presumption that the contents of an automobile are those of the person who operates the vehicle.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b91b6d274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Presumptions of law are either conclusive or subject to rebuttal. <eos/><bos/>If they are conclusive, they are rules of substantive law or estoppels.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b91b6d374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] For example, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="1992158808" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2e206d6274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Nodvin v. Plantation Pipeline Co.</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7b91b6d474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] the plaintiff accepted a deed which stated that the conveyance included an easement to a pipeline company. <eos/><bos/>Applying former O.C.G.A. § 24-4-24(b)(5),[<footnote.reference refid="I7b91dde074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] which covered conclusive presumptions of law, the court held the grantee was estopped from challenging the easement because the grantee had accepted the language of the deed.[<eos/><?page no="429"?><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b91dde174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="2003205279" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2e23057274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Beach v. Lipham</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7b91dde274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court concluded that the presumption of due care in a medical malpractice case is a rebuttable presumption of law. <eos/><bos/>Thus, <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“[i]t is a legal inference or assumption that physicians, nurses, and other medical professionals exercise due care and skill in their treatment of a patient based on their education, training, and experience. <eos/><bos/>To overcome the presumption in the typical case, the injured patient must present evidence from expert medical witnesses that the defendants did not exercise due care and skill in performing their services.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7b91dde374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Furthermore, the Georgia Supreme Court has recognized that in a criminal case, where allegations of ineffective assistance of counsel are made, a strong presumption arises that defendant&apos;s counsel performed reasonably, and the defendant bears the burden of overcoming this presumption.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b91dde474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The so-called presumption of fact may be a presumption or may be only an inference. <eos/><bos/><begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“In arriving at a verdict, the jury, from facts proved, and sometimes from the absence of counter evidence, may infer the existence of other facts reasonably and logically consequent on those proved.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0003"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7b91dde574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Federal Rules of Evidence do not define presumptions.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7b91b6d074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The definitions in former O.C.G.A. § 24-1-1 were not carried over into the new Evidence Code.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91b6d174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-20" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2e1f0dd074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-14-20</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91b6d274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="2048547588" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000999" ID="I2e1f5bf174d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hines v. State, 2019 WL 2574277 (Ga. Ct. App. 2019)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91b6d374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-26" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2e1fd12074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. §§ 24-14-26</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-27" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2e1fd12174d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">24-14-27</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-29" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2e1fd12274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">24-14-29</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91b6d474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="1992158808" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2e20bb8274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Nodvin v. Plantation Pipe Line Co., 204 Ga. App. 606, 610, 420 S.E.2d 322 (1992)</cite.query> (<case.history>abrogated on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="1998208955" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2e20bb8574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Yaali, Ltd. v. Barnes &amp; Noble, Inc., 269 Ga. 695, 506 S.E.2d 116 (1998)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91dde074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Now <cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-26" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2e2130b074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-14-26</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91dde174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator><?page no="429"?>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-21" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2e217ed074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-14-21</cite.query><?page no="429"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Supreme Court of Georgia has ruled on the validity of this Code section (former § 24-4-21) pertaining to the presumption of continued insanity. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="1993074816" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" w-pinpoint-page="492" ID="I2e221b1274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Nagel v. State, 262 Ga. 888, 427 S.E.2d 490, 492 (1993)</cite.query>, the court rejected the appellant&apos;s argument that the statutory presumption violated due process rights by creating a de facto irrebuttable presumption of insanity. <eos/><bos/>The court held that, while the jury is not bound by the opinions of either expert or lay witnesses, it may not disregard them; and the court&apos;s standard for review and the findings and conclusions required for that review insure that the presumption of insanity cannot be applied irrebuttably.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Also see <cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="1993202158" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2e22693274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Gross v. State, 210 Ga. App. 125, 435 S.E.2d 496 (1993)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91dde274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="2003205279" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2e232c8274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Beach v. Lipham, 276 Ga. 302, 578 S.E.2d 402 (2003)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91dde374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="2003205279" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2e23c8c274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Beach v. Lipham, 276 Ga. 302, 304, 578 S.E.2d 402 (2003)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91dde474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-serial-number="2033499726" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2e243df274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hicks v. State, 295 Ga. 268, 759 S.E.2d 509 (2014)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b91dde574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017239" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-9" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2e24b32074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-14-9</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 12:7<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
